On the first day of the second month in the second year after they had
 left the land of Egypt, the Eternal spoke to Moses in the desert of Sinai, within the Trysting tent, bidding him
 and Aaron 
 count up the total mem­bers of the community of Israel, clan by clan,
 family by family, and also number all the male individuals, head by head; 
 all Israelites over twenty years who were able for active service were to
 be numbered, company by company. 
 They were to take a representative of every clan, in each case the head
 of the family, 
 the names of the representa­tives were to be as follows. From Reuben,
 Elizur the son of Shedeur; 
 from Simeon, Shelumiel the son of Zurishaddai; 
 from Judah, Nahshon the son of Amminadab; 
 from Issachar, Nathaniel the son of Zuar; 
 from Zebulun, Eliab the son of Helon; 
 from the Josephites -- Ephraim, Elishama the son of Ammihud, and from
 Manasseh, Gamaliel the son of Pedahzur; 
 from Benjamin, Abidan the son of Gideoni; 
 from Dan, Ahiezer the son of Ammishaddai; 
 from Asher, Pagiel the son of Ochran; 
 from Gad, Eliasaph the son of Reuel; 
 from Naphtali, Ahira the son of Enan. 
 Such were the men selected from the com­munity, the leaders of their
 an­cestral clans, who were at the head of the septs in Israel. 
 Moses and Aaron took these men who have been named, 
 and mustered all the community on the first day of the second month,
 when they registered themselves, clan by clan, family by family, and had every indi­vidual over twenty numbered, 
 head by head, as the Eternal had ordered.  Moses numbered them in the
 desert thus.
